  "text": "To the best of our knowledge, this is the first study reporting epidemiological and phylogenetic analyses of Fusarium species infecting tomatoes in Khyber-Pakhtunkhwa province. Our study shows that Fusarium wilt is present in a majority of the tomato growing areas at all growth stages, most likely because of lack of sanitation, using infected seeds, and mono-culturing, which could lead to build-up of soil-borne inoculum. In addition, inappropriate use of fungicides could also lead to the development of fungicide-resistant strains thus increasing the prevalence and incidence of the disease [CITATION_1] .",
